S. Korean students and democratic�@patriots demanded
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, June 27 (KCNA) -- The spokesman for the National Democratic Front of South Korea (NDFSK) issued a statement on June 18 denouncing the South Korean rulers for their recently intensified repression of progressive students and democratic patriotic forces on false charges, according to the Seoul-based radio Voice of National Salvation.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The statement said:   The rulers of the "government for the people" have arrested 22 members of the Hanyang Organization for the anti-U.S. national salvation after labeling them as "forces for overthrowing the system" on charges that they disseminated the Juche idea at universities and in the army and orchestrated several demonstrations.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   It is an intolerable challenge to the progressive students and democratic patriotic forces desirous of independence, democracy and reunification.
   The South Korean rulers should stop the clumsy fascist repressive move at once and set free the imprisoned students and patriots without delay.

Kim  Ku remembered 
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, June 27 (KCNA) -- A meeting for remembering Kim  Ku was held here on Saturday on the occasion of the half centenary of his death.
   Present at the meeting were members of the National Reconciliation Council of the DPRK, those related to Kim  Ku's activities, members of compatriots delegations and visiting groups from abroad and other compatriots.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Honorary Chairman Sin Chang Gyun of the south headquarters of the National Alliance for the country's reunification, who is also chairman of the "preparatory committee to remember Paekbom Kim  Ku on half centenary of his death," personages from all sectors and reunification movement organizations of South Korea were invited to the meeting, but they could not come to it owing to the obstructive maneuvers of the South Korean authorities.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Addressing the meeting first, Kim  Yong Dae, chairman of the central committee of the Korean Social Democratic Party and chairman of the National Reconciliation Council, said:    Kim  Ku was not a communist, but a conscientious nationalist and patriot, who loved the country and the nation, desired the national sovereignty and independence from his early years, repudiated submission and dependence upon outsiders and opposed national division, Kim  Yong Dae said.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
He went on:   A particular mention should be made of the fact that  Kim  Ku, deeply moved by the great President Kim  Il Sung's patriotic initiative and warm love while attending the north-south joint conference held here in April Juche 37 (1948), keenly realized where the center for national unity was and where the cradle for the nation to live in was and worked for collaboration with communism, thus turning over a new leaf.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The respected Marshal Kim  Jong Il saw to it that his name was inscribed on the united front tower and the "National Reunification Prize" was awarded to him to convey his patriotic dedication down through the nation's history.
   Kim  Yong Dae called upon all the fellow countrymen in the north, south and abroad to rise up in the struggle to achieve national independence and great unity irrespective of differences in idea and system, political view and religious belief in hearty response to the five-point policy of great national unity.   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   He was followed by those related to Kim  Ku's activities and a delegate of overseas compatriots. 
   The poem "Dirge for Paekbom" created by South Koreans 50 years ago was recited at the meeting.
   The meeting was followed by a performance given by the state symphony orchestra on the theme of great national unity and reunification.

War hawks' outbursts under fire
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, June 27 (KCNA) -- There is a limit to our patience and self-restraint. Unlimited is our merciless retaliation against the provocateurs and aggressors. The South Korean war-thirsty elements are well advised to stop going berserk, clearly mindful who their rival is. This strong warning comes in a signed commentary of Rodong Sinmun today lashing out at the warlords of South Korea for their anti-north war agitation made at the recent "meeting of major commanders of the army."    They were reported to have repeated their absurd assertion about "northern limit line," crying for the "strengthened combat posture" and "sternly dealing with" someone's "provocations." &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Dismissing what the war hawks uttered, failing to draw a proper lesson from the west sea incident as disgusting, the commentary goes on: This incident was entirely attributable to the South Korean bellicose elements' intrusion into our inviolable territorial waters and their military provocations against us. The waters where this clash occurred indisputable belong to our territorial waters both in the light of the armistice agreement and the practice so far followed since the truce. This notwithstanding, the South Korean war hawks unilaterally set the so-called "northern limit line" which nobody recognizes. And they have carried on their armed provocations by illegally infiltrating scores of warships of various types into the territorial waters of our side since June 4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
  Unable to remain a mere onlooker to these reckless military provocations, navymen of the Korean People's Army meted out a deserved punishment to the intruders. 
  The South Korean bellicose elements are persisting in their military provocations against us in waters off the west coast, while floating cock-and-bull stories intended to hide the truth behind the incident and shift the blame for it onto us. This is an intolerable challenge to us as it was prompted by the criminal aim to ignite a war of aggression against the north come what may, backed by the U.S. war hawks.
